        <a name="PotterCanon" rel="nofollow" id="PotterCanon"></a>
    </p>
    <h3>Potter Canon <a href="#Contents" rel="nofollow">▲</a></h3>

    <p>First, what’s canon? Practically every reader takes the seven Harry Potter-titled books, PS to DH, as canon. Most
        will also take the books <em>Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them </em>and <em>Quidditch Through the
            Ages</em> as canon. Plenty of people use the films and even the video games to supplement this, but if your
        fic gives priority to the films over the books then you’re best off mentioning this at the beginning so that
        nobody has the wrong expectations. A significant minority of writers and readers ignore the <em>Fantastic
            Beasts</em> movies, in whole or in part, and you shouldn’t feel weird about doing the same (though, again,
        it might be good to telegraph that fact in some way <em>before </em>it becomes a plot-crucial point).</p>

    <p>If I say that something is "canon" or "canonical," without specifying further, then I'm probably talking about
        "Book+" Canon: The seven main books plus <em>Fantastic Beasts</em> and <em>Quidditch</em>.  </p>
    <ul>
        <li>I figure that anyone who’s reading this already knows about the <a
                href="https://harrypotter.fandom.com/wiki/Main_Page" rel="nofollow">Harry Potter Wiki</a>, but if you
            didn’t, now you do. Be warned that HPW is a mess, though. It insists on treating everything as canonical
            unless it specifically contradicts the books, which means that the Wiki’s vision of canon exists in a weird
            superposition where Death Eaters collapsed both the Brockdale Bridge and the Millennium Bridge, even though
            construction on the latter didn’t even begin until 1998: “Fudge refused to step down, and thus Voldemort
            ordered Death Eaters to cause the Brockdale Bridge and the Millennium Bridge to collapse.”</li>
        <li>Anyway, despite the Harry Potter Wiki’s penchant for treating LEGO Harry Potter as canonical, it is (like
            the real Wikipedia) still a decent starting point if you aren’t sure about something. In particular, its
            page on the <a href="https://harrypotter.fandom.com/wiki/1991%E2%80%931992_school_year"
                rel="nofollow">1991-1992 school year</a> has a list of every canonical professor and student attending
            Hogwarts at that time, with students organized by year.</li>
        <li>The <a href="https://www.hp-lexicon.org/" rel="nofollow">Harry Potter Lexicon</a> has much less information
            than HPW, but is far, far better sourced. I particularly like the <a
                href="https://www.hp-lexicon.org/timeline/character-timelines/voldemort-timeline/"
                rel="nofollow">Timeline of events in the life of Voldemort | Tom Riddle, Jr.</a></li>
        <li>In "<a
                href="https://old.reddit.com/r/HPfanfiction/comments/fiangw/article_a_crazily_comprehensive_canon_exploration/"
                rel="nofollow">Crazily Comprehensive Canon Exploration of Goblins</a>," Choice Caterpillar checks every
            canonical reference to goblins and gives a thorough analysis of what the books tell us about goblins. Backup
            <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220906011823/https://old.reddit.com/r/HPfanfiction/comments/fiangw/article_a_crazily_comprehensive_canon_exploration/"
                rel="nofollow">here</a>.</li>
        <li>White Hound’s "<a href="http://members.madasafish.com/~cj_whitehound/Fanfic/Sectumsempra.htm"
                rel="nofollow">Sectumsempra and the nature of curses</a>" makes an argument for the workings of
            Sectumsempra. Whether or not you agree, it’s probably good for a refresher on what canon does and doesn’t
            say about Sectumsempra and curses in general.</li>
        <li>White Hound wrote a comprehensive list of “<a
                href="http://members.madasafish.com/~cj_whitehound/Fanfic/birthdates.htm" rel="nofollow">Birthdates in
                the Harry Potter universe</a>.” Sorry, did I say “list?” I meant “essay.” 20,000 words.</li>
        <li><a href="https://www.potter-search.com/" rel="nofollow">Potter Search</a> allows you to search the text of
            all seven books.</li>
        <li><a href="http://www.accio-quote.org/" rel="nofollow">Accio Quote</a> collects a trove of quotes and comments
            by J. K. Rowling.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
