    <h3><a name="PotterFanon" rel="nofollow" id="PotterFanon"></a>Potter Fanon <a href="#Contents" rel="nofollow">▲</a>
    </h3>
    <ul>
        <li><a href="https://themonsterblogofmonsters.tumblr.com/" rel="nofollow">The Monster Blog of Monsters</a> has
            beasts, beings, diseases (e.g. <a
                href="https://themonsterblogofmonsters.tumblr.com/post/165949840280/lingua-franca-lingua-franca-disease"
                rel="nofollow">lingua franca</a>), spirits (e.g. <a
                href="https://themonsterblogofmonsters.tumblr.com/post/154264913704/animal-ghost-highly-unusual-phenomena-animal"
                rel="nofollow">animal ghosts</a>), magical substances and objects (e.g. <a
                href="https://themonsterblogofmonsters.tumblr.com/post/158868327292/goblin-ironwork-powerfully-enchanted-ironwork"
                rel="nofollow">goblin ironwork</a>), strange phenomena (e.g. <a
                href="https://themonsterblogofmonsters.tumblr.com/post/159916938311/filmic-dissipation-a-curious-phenomenon-found-in"
                rel="nofollow">filmic dissipation</a>), <a
                href="https://themonsterblogofmonsters.tumblr.com/magizoology" rel="nofollow">excerpts from fake
                articles</a>, and more. Much of it fails to fit the flavor of my personal canon(s), but it’s still a
            goldmine. </li>
        <li>You may want to skim White Hound’s “<a
                href="http://members.madasafish.com/~cj_whitehound/Fanfic/fanonvscanon.htm" rel="nofollow">Fanon versus
                canon</a>” essay. A lot of it is about Snape, but there are also sections like “<a
                href="http://members.madasafish.com/~cj_whitehound/Fanfic/fanonvscanon.htm#sherbet"
                rel="nofollow">Dumbledore habitually offers people sherbet lemons</a>,” “<a
                href="http://members.madasafish.com/~cj_whitehound/Fanfic/fanonvscanon.htm#dungeons" rel="nofollow">The
                dungeons of Hogwarts are cold</a>,” and “<a
                href="http://members.madasafish.com/~cj_whitehound/Fanfic/fanonvscanon.htm#James_as_Auror"
                rel="nofollow">James and Sirius were Aurors</a>.”</li>
        <li>Taure’s “<a
                href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1V0Ivrl_5ehWAQVDTiHVG395AM7i9Pgul/edit?usp=sharing&amp;ouid=117544339475577689457&amp;rtpof=true&amp;sd=true"
                rel="nofollow">Canon Plus</a>” document gives an overview of his version of canon, and touches on
            everything from the Gamp’s Law of Elemental Transfiguration (and its exceptions) to the number of Galleons
            in Harry Potter’s vault. </li>
        <li>Taure has also written on a "<a
                href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1S0CRSwFjiqPyC6NqikGH8QvJlAWuBhMK/edit?usp=sharing&amp;ouid=117544339475577689457&amp;rtpof=true&amp;sd=true"
                rel="nofollow">Small Wizarding World</a>," which "depicts a version of the wizarding world which is more
            integrated with the Muggle world as a sub-culture rather than a fully independent society." </li>
        <li>If you’re writing any kind of reinterpretation of the series, whether canon-compliant or fully AU, then you
            may be interested in reading the <a href="https://archive.org/details/ultimateunoffici00wate"
                rel="nofollow">Ultimate Unofficial Guide to the Mysteries of Harry Potter</a>. The book is hopelessly
            obsolete as a canon resource, but the “mysteries,” and especially the chapter on “Book 5 and Beyond,” can
            help you to see the series (especially the first four books) with fresh eyes. Quirrell doesn’t really have a
            place in most fanfics, but the Guide points out that Quirrell was only “left to die” by Voldemort; there’s
            some interesting wiggle room there, if you want to seize it. Not all of this analysis is all that great,
            though. The Guide seems to think that most relevant thing about the myth of Romulus and Remus is that Remus
            was killed by his brother, and not, say, that Remus was raised by a wolf. </li>
    </ul>
    <h4>Locations</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>White Hound’s <a
                href="http://members.madasafish.com/~cj_whitehound/Fanfic/Location_Location/Spinners_End.htm"
                rel="nofollow">essay on Spinner’s End</a>: what canon tells us, where in England it (and Cokeworth) may
            be, and what the houses may look like (inc. floorplans). </li>
        <li>White Hound has written a number of essays on how certain locations may fit into the wider world, both
            historically and geographically. She’s also written on <a
                href="http://members.madasafish.com/~cj_whitehound/Fanfic/Location_Location/Godrics_Hollow.htm"
                rel="nofollow">Godric’s Hollow</a>, <a
                href="http://members.madasafish.com/~cj_whitehound/Fanfic/Location_Location/Ottery_St_Catchpole.htm"
                rel="nofollow">Ottery St. Catchpole</a>, <a
                href="http://members.madasafish.com/~cj_whitehound/Fanfic/Location_Location/Tinworth.htm"
                rel="nofollow">Shell Cottage &amp; Tinworth</a>, and <a
                href="http://members.madasafish.com/~cj_whitehound/Fanfic/Location_Location/Little_Whinging.htm"
                rel="nofollow">Little Whinging</a>, and an essay that handles <a
                href="http://members.madasafish.com/~cj_whitehound/Fanfic/Location_Location/Grimmauld_Place_etc.htm"
                rel="nofollow">Grimmauld Place, the Ministry, and St. Mungo’s</a> together. Go <a
                href="http://members.madasafish.com/~cj_whitehound/Fanfic/Location_Location.htm" rel="nofollow">here</a>
            for a few more essays. Her <a
                href="http://members.madasafish.com/~cj_whitehound/Fanfic/Location_Location/other.htm"
                rel="nofollow">Other</a> page discusses Upper Flagley, Great &amp; Little Hangleton, Malfoy Manor, and
            the Forest of Dean.</li>
        <li><a href="https://www.deviantart.com/firephoenix86/art/12-Grimmauld-Place-Floor-plans-722668480"
                rel="nofollow">FirePhoenix86</a>, <a
                href="https://fyhjp.tumblr.com/post/437307781/floor-plan-of-12-grimmauld-place-click-to-view"
                rel="nofollow">fyhjp</a>, and <a
                href="https://www.deviantart.com/notsalony/art/12-Grimmauld-Place-cannon-121474398"
                rel="nofollow">Notsalony</a> have each drawn up floor plans for 12 Grimmauld Place.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
        <strong>Wands</strong>
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>“<a href="https://archiveofourown.org/works/42486126/chapters/106707771" rel="nofollow">Agata Gregorovich's
                Guide To Wandlore</a>,” by Faithless_3105, has lists of wand woods and wand cores (including botanical
            and mineral cores), and briefly discusses wandstaining, wands made from non-wood substances, and schools of
            magic. </li>
        <li>“<a href="https://archiveofourown.org/works/10193936/chapters/22638896" rel="nofollow">An Independent
                Wandmaker’s Guide for the Magical World</a>” is an incomplete AO3 mirror of the Wandmore tumblr. </li>
        <li><a href="https://wandmore.tumblr.com/" rel="nofollow">Wandmore</a> discusses wand cores (e.g. <a
                href="https://wandmore.tumblr.com/post/122625993653/hippogriff-feather-as-a-core"
                rel="nofollow">hippogriff feather</a>) and wand woods (e.g. <a
                href="https://wandmore.tumblr.com/coconut" rel="nofollow">coconut</a>), wandlore (e.g. <a
                href="https://wandmore.tumblr.com/post/164076274252/could-you-make-a-list-of-possible-woods-and-cores"
                rel="nofollow">Polish wand woods and cores</a>), wands for canon characters, and more. </li>
        <li>“<a href="https://www.wood-database.com/" rel="nofollow">The Wood Database</a>” collects an incredible
            amount of information about an incredible number of woods: common names, scientific name, size of the tree,
            dry weight of the wood, hardness, appearance, odor, workability… If you want to say more about a wand’s wood
            than just its magical properties, then make sure to consult this database. </li>
        <li><a href="https://wandmore.tumblr.com/wood" rel="nofollow">Wandmore</a>: “Wand lore, wand theories, and
            theorising the possible nature and character of a wand’s Master.”</li>
        <li>Witchcraft &amp; Wizardry’s <a href="http://wandw.wikidot.com/wandlore" rel="nofollow">page on Wandlore</a>.
        </li>
    </ul>
    <h3><a name="IRL" rel="nofollow" id="IRL"></a>IRL <a href="#Contents" rel="nofollow">▲</a></h3>
    <ul>
        <li>“<a href="https://archiveofourown.org/works/40064247/chapters/100338021#workskin" rel="nofollow">Classical
                Literature for Fandom Purposes</a>,” by splendide_mendax, is an AO3 guide to Greek and Latin literature.
        </li>
        <li><a href="https://www.artiscreation.com/Color_index_names.html" rel="nofollow">Color of Art Pigment
                Database</a>, with alternative names, chemical composition, and other facts (e.g. this or that pigment
            may be primarily used in inks) for each pigment. </li>
        <li>The Medieval Bestiary collects an incredible number of, uh, Medieval bestiaries. You can <a
                href="https://bestiary.ca/manuscript.htm" rel="nofollow">look at the manuscripts individually</a> or <a
                href="https://bestiary.ca/beasts.htm" rel="nofollow">read everything that is said about this or that
                beast</a>.</li>
        <li><a href="https://www.oldbookillustrations.com/" rel="nofollow">Old Book Illustrations</a>, <a
                href="https://suberic.net/~dmm/astro/constellations_t.html" rel="nofollow">New Constellation
                Symbols</a>, and <a href="https://suberic.net/~dmm/astro/moons.html"
                rel="nofollow">Astronomical/Astrological symbols for other planets’ moons</a>, all in the public domain.
        </li>
        <li>FamilySearch’s <a href="https://www.familysearch.org/en/blog/cousin-chart" rel="nofollow">Cousin
                Calculator</a> will let you determine the exact relationship between two distantly-related family
            members. For example, by cross-referencing the Black Family Tree, we can see that Draco and Ron are third
            cousins once removed, Scorpius and Albus (Potter) are fourth cousins once removed, and Sirius Black is his
            own third cousin.</li>
        <li>FamilySearch discusses occupations and other topics in great depth. Start with <a
                href="https://www.familysearch.org/en/wiki/British_Isles" rel="nofollow">their page on the British
                Isles</a> and progress in whatever direction makes the most sense: <a
                href="https://www.familysearch.org/en/wiki/England_Genealogy" rel="nofollow">England</a>, Ireland, <a
                href="https://www.familysearch.org/en/wiki/Scotland_Genealogy" rel="nofollow">Scotland</a>, <a
                href="https://www.familysearch.org/en/wiki/Wales_Genealogy" rel="nofollow">Wales</a>, etc. For example,
            the Wales page has a map of that country’s original historic counties, links to pages (with census
            information and other records) for each of those counties, a page on <a
                href="https://www.familysearch.org/en/wiki/Wales_Naming_Customs" rel="nofollow">Welsh naming
                customs</a>, another on <a href="https://www.familysearch.org/en/wiki/Wales_Taxation"
                rel="nofollow">taxation in Wales</a>, etc. Besides these and similar pages, the single most useful
            resource may be the pages linked under “<a
                href="https://www.familysearch.org/en/wiki/England_Business_and_Occupations#Historical_Occupations"
                rel="nofollow">England Business and Occupations</a>,” which you should peruse if you would like to know
            more about barkers, drovers, or postal workers. </li>
        <li>Riddles and more riddles: <a
                href="https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1pfa6ATwSThuScW2wM_k8zJ0uKYyY3ZracoO3By3k_Es/edit#gid=0"
                rel="nofollow">D100 of Tricks, Puzzles, and Riddles</a>; <a
                href="http://farlandworld.com/files/riddles1.pdf" rel="nofollow">Riddles for DMs</a>.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
        <strong>British and Irish Stuff</strong>
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li><a href="https://www.shakespeareauthorship.com/bd/" rel="nofollow">Biographical Index of English Drama
                Before 1660</a>.</li>
        <li><a href="https://www.oxford-royale.com/articles/a-guide-to-british-newspapers/" rel="nofollow">Black and
                White and Read All Over: A Guide to British Newspapers</a>.</li>
        <li><a href="https://themori-witch.tumblr.com/post/689449386308141056/english-folktraditional-names-for-common-plants"
                rel="nofollow">English Folk/Traditional Names for Common Plants &amp; Herbs</a>.</li>
        <li><a href="https://www.theedkins.co.uk/jo/units/weight.htm" rel="nofollow">Imperial Measures of Weight</a>.
        </li>
        <li><a href="https://www.metoffice.gov.uk/research/climate/maps-and-data/uk-climate-averages/gcj8q3emu"
                rel="nofollow">UK climate averages</a>.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
        <strong>Food</strong>
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>Samantha Kelly’s blog, Chasing London Street Food, and in particular her post, “<a
                href="https://samanthachristinekelly.wordpress.com/2014/02/15/part-1-street-food-revolution-the-history-of-street-food/"
                rel="nofollow">The Evolution of Street Food</a>,” is very useful if you want to spice up Diagon Alley
            and other wixen spaces with open-air fare.</li>
        <li><a href="https://www.countryfile.com/wildlife/farming-calendar-a-year-in-the-life-of-a-british-farmer"
                rel="nofollow">Guide to the farming calendar: a year in the life of a British farmer</a>.</li>
        <li><a href="https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/discover/gardening-tips/guide-to-seasonal-food"
                rel="nofollow">Guide to seasonal foods</a> (when to buy, harvest, plant, or sow)</li>
        <li>Scotland Food and Drink has a <a
                href="https://web.archive.org/web/20230603053358/https://foodanddrink.scot/resources/seasonality-calendar/"
                rel="nofollow">seasonality calendar</a> for native fruits, herbs, seafood, vegetables, etc. You can also
            consult <a href="https://www.visitscotland.com/things-to-do/food-drink/seasonal-food-calendar"
                rel="nofollow">this other seasonality calendar</a> on Visit Scotland, or <a
                href="https://www.nutritionscotland.org/resources/whats-in-season/" rel="nofollow">this other, other
                seasonality calendar</a>, which focuses on fruits and vegetables.</li>
        <li><a href="https://www.charlesdowding.co.uk/resources/sowing-timeline" rel="nofollow">Sowing timeline for
                vegetables</a>.</li>
        <li><a href="https://www.watermanscountrysupplies.co.uk/blog/latest-news/our-uk-farming-calendar/"
                rel="nofollow">UK Farming Calendar</a></li>
        <li>Wild Food UK has a <a href="https://www.wildfooduk.com/mushroom-guide/?" rel="nofollow">list of
                mushrooms</a> and another <a href="https://www.wildfooduk.com/wild-plant-guide/" rel="nofollow">list of
                plants</a>, filterable by edibility and season.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
        <strong>Language</strong>
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>For old timey words, I recommend <a href="https://1828.mshaffer.com/" rel="nofollow">1828 Webster’s
                Dictionary</a>. If your needs are even more archaic than that, then check out the <a
                href="https://www.oldenglishtranslator.co.uk/" rel="nofollow">Old English to Modern English
                Translator</a>. </li>
        <li><a href="https://www.cornishdictionary.org.uk/about?locale=en" rel="nofollow">Cornish Dictionary</a>,
            exactly what it sounds like. </li>
        <li><a href="https://www.lexilogos.com/keyboard/greek_conversion.htm" rel="nofollow">Greek &gt; Latin alphabet
                conversion</a>, to turn Διογένης into Diogénēs, for example.</li>
        <li>If you’re worried that a word might be too modern for wixes to use (or conversely, you feel that a word is
            too modern but aren’t sure what to replace it with) then I recommend <a href="http://wiktionary.org/"
                rel="nofollow">Wiktionary</a> and the <a href="http://etymonline.com/" rel="nofollow">Online Etymology
                Dictionary</a>.</li>
        <li><a href="https://www.gutenberg.org/files/20023/20023-h/20023-h.htm" rel="nofollow">The Letters of Queen
                Victoria</a> and <a href="https://archive.org/details/howtowritelette01westgoog/page" rel="nofollow">How
                to Write Letters: A Manual of Correspondence</a> are useful if you want to ape the style of Victorian
            letter-writing. <a
                href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130601193929/http://www.erasofelegance.com/etiquette/letterwriting.html"
                rel="nofollow">The Victorian Art of Letterwriting</a> is much more condensed.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
        <strong>Maps</strong>
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li><a href="https://anvaka.github.io/city-roads/" rel="nofollow">City Roads</a> will render all of the roads in
            a specified city, with the ability to zoom in or out. </li>
        <li>Maps on the Web is a treasure trove: (11th century / Founding of Hogwarts) <a
                href="https://mapsontheweb.zoom-maps.com/post/727353622545022976/commercial-routes-in-medieval-age"
                rel="nofollow">Commercial routes in Medieval Europe</a>, <a
                href="https://mapsontheweb.zoom-maps.com/post/190696562460/europe-at-the-turn-of-the-11th-century"
                rel="nofollow">Europe in 1000</a>, <a
                href="https://mapsontheweb.zoom-maps.com/post/110246780986/the-north-sea-empire-as-ruled-by-cnut-the-great-as"
                rel="nofollow">North Sea Empire of Cnut the Great</a>, <a
                href="https://mapsontheweb.zoom-maps.com/post/185083731130/normans-conquest-of-england-via-reddit"
                rel="nofollow">Norman Conquest of England</a>, <a
                href="https://mapsontheweb.zoom-maps.com/post/117854769317/the-counties-of-england-at-the-time-of-the"
                rel="nofollow">Counties of England in 1086</a>; (17th century / Statute of Secrecy) <a
                href="https://mapsontheweb.zoom-maps.com/post/622458346816094208/iroquois-empire-1626-1681"
                rel="nofollow">Iroquois Empire</a>; <a
                href="https://mapsontheweb.zoom-maps.com/post/728611785010184192/the-ottoman-empire-at-its-height-in-the-17th"
                rel="nofollow">Ottoman Empire</a>, <a
                href="https://mapsontheweb.zoom-maps.com/post/727990049645494272/new-netherlands-1614-1675"
                rel="nofollow">New Netherlands</a>; (Other maps) <a
                href="https://mapsontheweb.zoom-maps.com/post/187817312431/england-during-the-reign-of-king-aethelstan"
                rel="nofollow">England 924-39</a>, <a
                href="https://mapsontheweb.zoom-maps.com/post/730776626217074688/the-balkans-in-1410-amid-the-ottoman-civil-war"
                rel="nofollow">Balkans in 1410</a>, <a
                href="https://mapsontheweb.zoom-maps.com/post/727992159373082624/map-of-europe-with-rivers-by-mercator-1595"
                rel="nofollow">1595 Map of Europe with rivers</a>, <a
                href="https://mapsontheweb.zoom-maps.com/post/727736472748376064/europe-in-1700" rel="nofollow">Europe
                in 1700</a>, <a
                href="https://mapsontheweb.zoom-maps.com/post/728171717680414720/intelligibility-between-european-languages-by"
                rel="nofollow">Intelligibility between European languages</a>.</li>
        <li><a href="https://www.oldmapsonline.org/" rel="nofollow">Old Maps Online</a> is exactly what it sounds like.
            Useful for premodern eras, working out possible countries on the magical side of the Statute of Secrecy,
            etc. </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
        <strong>Names</strong>
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>For the meanings of given names, I recommend starting at <a href="http://www.behindthename.com/"
                rel="nofollow">Behind the Name</a>. </li>
        <li>For the meanings of surnames, I recommend starting at <a href="https://familysearch.org/en/surname"
                rel="nofollow">FamilySearch.org</a> and following it up with the <a href="https://www.surnamedb.com/"
                rel="nofollow">Internet Surname Database</a>, which usually gives more information about family history
            than FamilySearch. For distribution, the best site is generally <a href="https://en.geneanet.org/surnames/"
                rel="nofollow">Geneanet</a>, which allows you to refer only to records in a specific span of time from
            1500 to 2023, and occasionally has information that isn't available on FamilySearch. If you're having
            trouble identifying a region that shows up on Geneanet, then cross-referencing the name on <a
                href="https://www.ancestry.co.uk/learn/facts?geo_a=r&amp;geo_s=uk&amp;geo_t=uk&amp;geo_v=2.0.0&amp;o_iid=41012&amp;o_lid=41012&amp;o_sch=Web+Property"
                rel="nofollow">Ancestry</a> will often help. If all else fails, you might be able to find track down a
            family on <a href="https://www.wikitree.com/" rel="nofollow">WikiTree</a>, and <a
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Main_Page" rel="nofollow">Wikipedia</a> is always a good last
            reference if you want to be really thorough. If you're lucky, you might even find additional resources to
            check. <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/Wiktionary:Main_Page" rel="nofollow">Wiktionary</a> has also
            come in handy for me from time to time.</li>
        <li>For surnames related to places, <a href="https://www.heritagegateway.org.uk/gateway/"
                rel="nofollow">Heritage Gateway</a> and <a href="https://epns.nottingham.ac.uk/" rel="nofollow">Survey
                of English Place-Names</a> can help you out. </li>
        <li>Finally, don't discount Googling <samp>&lt;name_here&gt; "surname" </samp>and following whatever links look
            promising. </li>
        <li><a href="https://www.s-gabriel.org/names/maridonna/shipnames/" rel="nofollow">Ship Names from 1480-01</a>.
        </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
        <strong>Timelines</strong>
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>Aca Goldsmith wrote <a
                href="https://web.archive.org/web/20180520184101/https://acagoldsmith.tumblr.com/post/137123489501/tom-riddle-timeline-1926-1940"
                rel="nofollow">a timeline from 1926 to 1940</a>, covering canonical events in Tom Riddle’s life and the
            Second World War. </li>
        <li><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20190105051108/http://www.cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch68.htm"
                rel="nofollow">Chronology of the Troubles, 1968 - 2002</a>.</li>
    </ul>
